2\sin(x-y) = \sin(x+y)
\displaystyle \frac{\tan(x)}{\tan(y)}
\sin(x+y)=\sin x\cos y+\cos x\sin y=\cos x\cos y(\tan x+\tan y)
\sin(x-y)=\sin x\cos y-\cos x\sin y=\cos x\cos y(\tan x-\tan y)
\cos x\text{ and }\cos y
\cos x\cos y
 \begin{align} 2\sin(x-y) &= \sin(x+y) & \text{so, by definition}\\ 2(\sin x \cos y-\cos x\sin y) &= \sin x\cos y + \cos x\sin y & \text{so}\\ 2\sin x \cos y-2\cos x\sin y &= \sin x\cos y + \cos x\sin y & \text{collect terms to get}\\ \sin x\cos y &= 3\cos x\sin y & \text{divide by $\cos x\cos y$}\\ \tan x &= 3\tan y \end{align} 
 \frac{\tan x}{\tan y} = 3 
